            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Ideal Gas Law Formula</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-lg mb-1 text-center">\( PV = nRT \)</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li><strong>P</strong> = pressure of the gas</li>
                  <li><strong>V</strong> = volume of the gas</li>
                  <li><strong>n</strong> = amount of gas (in moles)</li>
                  <li><strong>R</strong> = universal gas constant</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>T</strong> = absolute temperature (in kelvins)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>Rearranging the Ideal Gas Law</h2>
              <p>
                Starting from \( PV = nRT \), you can solve for any variable:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Pressure</strong>: \( P = \dfrac{nRT}{V} \)</li>
                <li><strong>Volume</strong>: \( V = \dfrac{nRT}{P} \)</li>
                <li><strong>Moles</strong>: \( n = \dfrac{PV}{RT} \)</li>
                <li><strong>Temperature</strong>: \( T = \dfrac{PV}{nR} \)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically chooses the correct rearranged form
                based on which variable you select to solve for.
              </p>

              <h2>Common Values of the Gas Constant R</h2>
              <p>
                The numerical value of \( R \) depends on the units you use for
                pressure and volume. Some widely used forms are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \( R = 0.082057 \,\text{L·atm·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1} \) (P in
                  atm, V in L)
                </li>
                <li>
                  \( R = 8.314462618 \,\text{J·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1} \) (P in
                  Pa, V in m³)
                </li>
                <li>
                  \( R = 62.36367 \,\text{L·mmHg·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1} \) (P
                  in mmHg, V in L)
                </li>
                <li>
                  \( R = 0.0831446 \,\text{L·bar·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1} \) (P
                  in bar, V in L)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our calculator lets you pick any of these or enter a custom
                value if you are working in specialized units.
              </p>

              <h2>Unit Requirements and Conversions</h2>
              <p>
                To use the ideal gas law correctly, you must use a
                <strong>consistent set of units</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Temperature</strong> must always be in kelvins (K).
                  The calculator converts from °C and °F automatically using:
                  <ul>
                    <li>\( T(K) = T(°C) + 273.15 \)</li>
                    <li>\( T(K) = \dfrac{5}{9}[T(°F) - 32] + 273.15 \)</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pressure</strong> can be entered as Pa, kPa, atm, bar,
                  mmHg, or psi. Internally, the calculator converts to a base
                  unit that matches your chosen R.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Volume</strong> can be entered as m³, L, mL, or ft³.
                  Again, the calculator converts to the appropriate base unit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moles</strong> can be entered as mol or mmol (1 mol =
                  1000 mmol).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>When Does the Ideal Gas Law Apply?</h2>
              <p>The ideal gas law is an approximation that works best when:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Pressure is relatively low (molecules are far apart).</li>
                <li>
                  Temperature is moderate to high (well above the condensation
                  point).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Intermolecular forces and molecular volumes are negligible.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Under extreme conditions (very high pressure, very low
                temperature, or near phase changes), real gases deviate from
                ideal behavior. In those cases, more advanced equations of state
                (e.g. van der Waals, Redlich–Kwong, Peng–Robinson) are used.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked Example</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Problem.</strong> How many moles of an ideal gas are
                contained in a 10.0 L container at 2.00 atm and 25 °C?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert temperature to kelvins:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \( T = 25 + 273.15 = 298.15 \,\text{K} \)
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use \( R = 0.082057 \,\text{L·atm·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1} \)
                  (compatible with atm and L).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use \( n = \dfrac{PV}{RT} \):
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \( n =
                    \dfrac{(2.00\,\text{atm})(10.0\,\text{L})}{(0.082057\,\text{L·atm·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1})(298.15\,\text{K})}
                    \) <br />
                    \( n \approx \dfrac{20.0}{24.47} \approx 0.817 \,\text{mol}
                    \)
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator reproduces this result automatically when you
                enter the same values and choose to solve for
                <strong>n</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Physical Meaning</h2>
              <p>The ideal gas law combines several simpler gas laws:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Boyle’s law</strong>: at constant T and n, \( P
                  \propto 1/V \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Charles’s law</strong>: at constant P and n, \( V
                  \propto T \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avogadro’s law</strong>: at constant P and T, \( V
                  \propto n \)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Together, they imply that for a fixed amount of gas, the product
                \( PV \) is proportional to the absolute temperature \( T \).
                The proportionality constant per mole is the universal gas
                constant \( R \).
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

              <h3>Why do we need absolute temperature (K) instead of °C?</h3>
              <p>
                Absolute temperature in kelvins is directly proportional to the
                average kinetic energy of gas molecules. Using °C or °F would
                shift the zero point and break the proportionality, leading to
                incorrect relationships between pressure, volume, and
                temperature.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I mix units, like atm for pressure and m³ for volume?</h3>
              <p>
                You can, but then you must choose a compatible value of \( R \)
                or convert units. Our calculator handles the conversions
                internally, but conceptually you should always ensure that the
                units of \( P \), \( V \), and \( R \) are consistent.
              </p>

              <h3>How is the ideal gas law related to kinetic theory?</h3>
              <p>
                Kinetic molecular theory shows that pressure arises from
                molecules colliding with container walls. From this microscopic
                picture, one can derive that \( PV = Nk_B T \), where \( N \) is
                the number of molecules and \( k_B \) is Boltzmann’s constant.
                Using \( n = N/N_A \) and \( R = N_A k_B \) leads directly to \(
                PV = nRT \).
              </p>
